# GROUP BY & HAVING (Very Important)

This is one of the most frequently asked SQL topics in Java Developer interviews.

Use the same table:

| id | name  | department | salary |
| -- | ----- | ---------- | ------ |
| 1  | John  | IT         | 50000  |
| 2  | Mary  | HR         | 40000  |
| 3  | David | IT         | 60000  |
| 4  | Sara  | Finance    | 55000  |
| 5  | Tom   | HR         | 45000  |

---

# What is GROUP BY?

Used to group rows having the same value.

### Example

Without GROUP BY:

```sql
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM employee;
```

Output:

```text
5
```

Counts all employees.

---

With GROUP BY:

```sql
SELECT department,
       COUNT(*)
FROM employee
GROUP BY department;
```

Output:

| department | count |
| ---------- | ----- |
| IT         | 2     |
| HR         | 2     |
| Finance    | 1     |

Grouped by department.

---

# Problem 1

Find number of employees in each department.

```sql
SELECT department,
       COUNT(*) AS employee_count
FROM employee
GROUP BY department;
```

Output:

| department | employee_count |
| ---------- | -------------- |
| IT         | 2              |
| HR         | 2              |
| Finance    | 1              |

---

# Problem 2

Find total salary in each department.

```sql
SELECT department,
       SUM(salary) AS total_salary
FROM employee
GROUP BY department;
```

Output:

| department | total_salary |
| ---------- | ------------ |
| IT         | 110000       |
| HR         | 85000        |
| Finance    | 55000        |

